Throughout her 40+ years of public service, Waters has been on the cutting edge, tackling difficult & controversial issues. She combines strong legislative & public policy acumen & high visibility in Democratic Party activities w/ an unusual ability to do grassroots organizing.

She made history as the 1st woman & African American Chair of the House Financial Services Committee. A member of Congressional Democratic Leadership, Waters serves as a member of the Steering & Policy Committee & Co-Chair of the bipartisan Congressional Task Force on Alzheimers

She was appointed to the Appropriations Committee & elected the 1st woman chair of the Congressional Black Caucus(CBC). Burke’s most notable distinction occurred in 1973, when she became the 1st Congresswoman to give birth & be granted maternity leave while serving in Congress!

This saturday’s spotlight goes to: Yvonne Brathwaite Burke! In 1966 Yvonne became the first African–American woman elected to the California assembly. In 1972 she became the first black woman from California (and one of only three black women ever) elected to the House.

51 years ago Shirley Chisholm of NY became the 1st African-American Congresswoman. She was a Representative who blazed her own trail. She gave voice to women, African Americans, Latinos, and the poor. She once told an interviewer, “My power comes from the people.”

She campaigned for global peace and for racial and social justice for gay rights and women’s rights until her death, at age 78. While we celebrate the great MLK we cannot forget the woman who was right there with him every step of the way.

Before MLK, Coretta Scott was a civil rights activist & together they fought discrimination & poverty. After his death, she protected & expanded MLK’s legacy. “I am an activist” she said after his death. “I didn’t just emerge after Martin died—I was always there and involved.”
